\begin_layout Title
On Plouffe's Ramanujan Identities
\end_layout

\begin_layout Author
Linas Vepštas 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Email
<linasvepstas@gmail.com>
\end_layout

\begin_layout Date
14 May 2006 Revised 27 November 2010
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
Recently, Simon Plouffe has discovered a number of identities for the Riemann
 zeta function at odd integer values.
 These identities are obtained numerically and are inspired by a prototypical
 series for Apéry's constant given by Ramanujan:
\begin_inset Formula \[
\zeta(3)=\frac{7\pi^{3}}{180}-2\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\frac{1}{n^{3}\left(e^{2\pi n}-1\right)}\]

\end_inset

Such sums follow from a general relation given by Ramanujan, which is rediscover
ed and proved here using complex analytic techniques.
 The general relation is used to derive many of Plouffe's identities as
 corollaries.
 The resemblance of the general relation to the structure of theta functions
 and modular forms is briefly sketched.
\end_layout

