\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Inspired by an identity for 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta(3)$
\end_inset

 given in Ramanujan's notebooks 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "chapter 14, formulas 25.1 and 25.3"
key "Ber-II"

\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\zeta(3)=\frac{7\pi^{3}}{180}-2\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\frac{1}{n^{3}\left(e^{2\pi n}-1\right)}\]

\end_inset

Plouffe describes a set of similar identities
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Plo98"

\end_inset

,
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Plo06"

\end_inset

 that were discovered numerically using arbitrary-precision software.
 For example, Plouffe gives an identity for 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta(7)$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\zeta(7)=\frac{19\pi^{7}}{56700}-2\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\frac{1}{n^{7}\left(e^{2\pi n}-1\right)}\]

\end_inset

This text provides an analytically derived formula for expressions of this
 type.
 The resulting general formula, valid for integer 
\begin_inset Formula $m\ge1$
\end_inset

, is 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray*}
\zeta(4m-1) & = & -2\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\frac{1}{n^{4m-1}\left(e^{2\pi n}-1\right)}\\
 & - & \frac{1}{2}\;(2\pi)^{4m-1}\;\sum_{j=0}^{2m}\left(-1\right)^{j}\frac{B_{2j}}{(2j)!}\frac{B_{4m-2j}}{(4m-2j)!}\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{k}$
\end_inset

 is the 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

'th Bernoulli number.
 The above is a special case of a yet more general formula, derived and
 presented in a later section, allowing pairs of such sums to be related.
 From this, one may obtain expressions such as
\begin_inset Formula \[
\zeta(3)=\frac{37\pi^{3}}{900}-\frac{2}{5}\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\frac{1}{n^{3}}\left[\frac{4}{e^{\pi n}-1}+\frac{1}{e^{4\pi n}-1}\right]\]

\end_inset

There are an (uncountable) infinity of similar sums, each giving a different
 series summation for 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta(4m-1)$
\end_inset

.
 Taking linear combinations of these, one may choose to cancel the zeta
 terms, to obtain summations for odd powers of 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, for example, combining the above with Ramanujan's series for Apéry's
 constant, one gets:
\begin_inset Formula \[
\frac{\pi^{3}}{180}=\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\frac{1}{n^{3}}\left[\frac{4}{e^{\pi n}-1}-\frac{5}{e^{2\pi n}-1}+\frac{1}{e^{4\pi n}-1}\right]\]

\end_inset

Again, there are an uncountable infinity of such relations.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Plouffe also notes similar relations for the other odd integers; for example,
 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\zeta(5)=\frac{\pi^{5}}{294}-\frac{72}{35}\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\frac{1}{n^{5}\left(e^{2\pi n}-1\right)}-\frac{2}{35}\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\frac{1}{n^{5}\left(e^{2\pi n}+1\right)}\]

\end_inset

The general form for this type of expression may be shown to be 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{gather*}
\left[1+(-4)^{m}-2^{4m+1}\right]\zeta(4m+1)\qquad\qquad\qquad\qquad\qquad\\
\quad=2\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\frac{1}{n^{4m+1}\left(e^{2\pi n}+1\right)}\qquad\qquad\qquad\qquad\qquad\\
\qquad+2\left[2^{4m+1}-(-4)^{m}\right]\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\frac{1}{n^{4m+1}\left(e^{2\pi n}-1\right)}\qquad\\
\qquad\qquad+(2\pi)^{4m+1}\sum_{j=0}^{m}(-4)^{m+j}\frac{B_{4m-4j+2}}{(4m-4j+2)!}\frac{B_{4j}}{(4j)!}\\
\qquad\qquad\qquad+\frac{1}{2}(2\pi)^{4m+1}\;\sum_{j=0}^{2m+1}(-4)^{j}\frac{B_{4m-2j+2}}{(4m-2j+2)!}\frac{B_{2j}}{(2j)!}\end{gather*}

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The methods described in this text also allow for a large generalization
 of these types of sums.
 Defining 
\begin_inset Formula \[
P_{k}(\tau)=\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\frac{1}{n^{k}\left(e^{2\pi in\tau}-1\right)}\]

\end_inset

these generalizations follow from a modular equation relating 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{k}(\tau)$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{k}(-1/\tau)$
\end_inset

 for odd integers 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

, the derivation and proof of which is the one of the main topics of this
 note.
 The modular relation is not new; it appears in Ramanujan's Notebooks 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "Chapter 14 Entry 21"
key "Ber-II"

\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{multline*}
\alpha^{-n}\left\{ \frac{1}{2}\zeta\left(2n+1\right)+\sum_{k=1}^{\infty}\frac{k^{2n-1}}{e^{2\alpha k}-1}\right\} \\
\qquad=(-\beta)^{-n}\left\{ \frac{1}{2}\zeta\left(2n+1\right)+\sum_{k=1}^{\infty}\frac{k^{2n-1}}{e^{2\beta k}-1}\right\} \\
\qquad\qquad-2^{2n}\sum_{k=0}^{n+1}(-1)^{k}\frac{B_{2k}}{(2k)!}\frac{B_{2n+2-2k}}{(2n+2-2k)!}\alpha^{n+1-k}\beta^{k}\end{multline*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha>0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta>0$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\beta=\pi^{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 any positive integer.
 Berndt implies that this formula is the most studied of all the notebooks;
 it has been independently discovered perhaps a half-dozen times, and proven
 twice as often.
 It has been generalized to 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

-functions, and to rational values of 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

; Berndt provides a long list
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Ber-II"

\end_inset

 of the various proofs and generalizations made.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Much of this paper is devoted to (yet another! independently discovered)
 proof of this relation, followed by a series of lemmas that provide the
 connection to Plouffe's results.
 In searching for curious and interesting special cases of this relation,
 one senses that only the tip of the iceberg has been seen.
 Unexplored possibilities include, for example, considering 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau\in\mathbb{Q}[i]$
\end_inset

, the field of Gaussian rationals, or from considering Diophantine roots
 of quadratics.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The rest of this paper is roughly laid out as follows: The second section
 provides a review of previous related results.
 The third section gives a relationship between the sums and the polylogarithm,
 and thence to an integral on the complex plane.
 The fourth section examines the related contour integral, which is easily
 integrated via Cauchy's residue theorem to give a finite sum involving
 the Bernoulli numbers.
 The fifth section relates the contour integral to the polylogarithm integral,
 thus resulting in a functional equation for 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{k}(\tau)$
\end_inset

.
 The sixth section applies the functional equation, providing a variety
 of lemmas, many of which explain Plouffe's discoveries.
 The seventh section give a pair of relationships on the Bernoulli numbers
 that arise naturally in this context.
 The eighth section explores the modular nature of the relations on 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{k}(\tau)$
\end_inset

, followed by a conclusion.
 An appendix gives a derivation of an integral representation of the polylogarit
hm, that is central to the analysis.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Related sums
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A large number of similar sums have been explored before; this section reviews
 some of these.
 Perhaps the most forthright is a sum given by Ramanujan in a famous letter
 to Hardy
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Har21"

\end_inset

, stating that 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\frac{1^{13}}{e^{2\pi}-1}+\frac{2^{13}}{e^{4\pi}-1}+\frac{3^{13}}{e^{6\pi}-1}+\cdots=\frac{1}{24}\]

\end_inset

A generalization of this sum, 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\frac{n^{4k+1}}{e^{2\pi n}-1}=\frac{B_{4k+2}}{4(2k+1)}\]

\end_inset

is proved by Berndt
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Ber77"

\end_inset

, and attributed to Glaisher
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Gla1889"

\end_inset

.
 This and many related results are derived by Zucker
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Zuc79"

\end_inset

, based on the theory of Jacobian elliptic functions.
 A similar result is stated by Apostol in the form of an exercise
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "see exercise 15 at end of chapter 1."
key "Apo90"

\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula \[
\sum_{n=1;n\mbox{ odd}}^{\infty}\frac{n^{4k+1}}{1+e^{n\pi}}=\frac{2^{4k+1}-1}{8k+4}B_{4k+2}\]

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

