\begin_layout Standard
In this form, the relation to modular forms becomes the most immediate.
 Consider the Lambert series:
\begin_inset Formula \[
\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\frac{1}{n^{s}}\frac{q^{n}}{1-q^{n}}=-\zeta(s)-P_{s}(q)=\sum_{m=1}^{\infty}\sigma_{-s}(m)q^{m}\]

\end_inset

Here, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{s}(m)$
\end_inset

 is the divisor function: 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\sigma_{s}(m)=\sum_{n|m}\; n^{s}\]

\end_inset

with the notation 
\begin_inset Formula $n|m$
\end_inset

 denoting that the sum extends over all divisors 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

.
 This should be compared to the Eisenstein series 
